caption: Amazing breakfast sandwiches. Great outdoor dining situation with plenty of seating.

Tagliatelle Bolognese are a good benchmark for a pasta restaurant, because they can’t handle mediocrity. If the ragu hasn’t simmered long enough or if it’s not rich enough, it will instantly taste like any bland industrial tomato sauce.  Al di la’s Bolognese is some of the best I’ve had, in fact it’s my favorite in NYC (along with the one from Emporio). The pasta is always perfectly al dente, the sauce is rich and buttery, thick and doesn’t taste too much like tomato, simply excellent 👌  Their cavatelli are less impressive, but still good.
Clean
The food was good, nothing to crazy or overly priced. The service was super friendly and sweet. It was pretty chilly outdoors so the food did get cold easily, but a super cute place.
Ordered takeout for parents food is mediocre. Wouldn’t recommend. Overpriced as well, agree with a previous review, other Italian restaurants are certainly better quality.
The food was delicious and service great even though it was pretty cold and outdoors. Loved the portions. The prices were reasonable too for the quality. Cute location as well
Best Italian food in Park Slope!

I don’t understand the hype of this place.  Coming from an actual Italian, their food is horrible.  Tried it once and my whole family got different meals, after the first bite we all spit out our food in disgust.  Their sauce tastes worse than if they were to use canned sauce from the supermarket.  La Villa and Scottaditto are both amazing restaurants with actual and delicious Italian cuisine.  Stop eating here when there are much better options just blocks away.

We have been going here for years and it is the closest thing to authentic northern Italian food we have had in New York City. Everything is always fresh and amazing. We always get the spaghetti neri, paccheri pasta, and the saltimbocca alla romana.  We have been enjoying takeout (and their coffee shop) always get cannot wait for indoor dining to be back for the proper experience so we can snack on their delicious bread and butter again too (photo from 2019).

Top notch restaurant with a local Italian trattoria feel.  A landmark of Park Slope that doesn't rest on its laurels. They keep impressing me every time I go. Especially now when dining is restricted, they put in the time, money, and effort to build comfortable heated outdoor dining areas for their customers.
The food was served on schedule and to our taste. Additionally, the serving size becomes more than ample considering the rate and season.
This place clearly knows how to take care of their clients. Always with a welcoming mindset. The food is affordably priced, always flavorful and clean.

I frequent this marvelous  place every couple of days since I like the  special atmosphere that is characterizes this restaurant. The staff is very friendly and professional. The service is exceptionally quick. Most important, the food you eat is exceptionaly good. I frequent often and I was always happy. The price is fair. I suggest this restaurant to my friends and family.
Still one of the best, even in a pandemic.

As a local real estate agent I enjoy visiting several food spots in the area and ai di la Trattoria is one of them I came across.  Overall a great Italian restaurant. The SPAGHETTI NERI ALLA CHITARRA is out of this world!

Current menu (October 2020) - tasty as always!

Had Autumn Market Salad (good), tagliatelle al ragu (very good), paccheri with pork shoulder ragu (fantastic), creamy polenta (good), and  baby carrots with yogurt (meh).  For dessert, three winners: mascarpone panna cotta with blueberries, pear & chocolate cake, and affogato with brittle.  I'd prefer china when eating out, but disposable containers and utensils are how places are getting by.

Park Slope favorite. Go to The Wine Bar next door, it has a better atmosphere with the same menu.  Do not bring a vegetarian or a vegan here, they serve rabbit. It's delicious. But some people are offended by eating cute animals. I judge based on character, not species level of cuteness.  Update: outdoor pandemic menu has no rabbit. So it's safe for those offended by cute eats. All animals are average looking.

This is not only my favorite Italian restaurant in New York, it is my favorite restaurant, full stop. Amazing pasta laid back atmosphere, and though many visitors might not know it, an important shrine of sorts for Billy Joel fans. Back in the 80s the space was an automotive garage and was used as the location for the video for Mr. Joel's hit Uptown Girl. Every year fans of Mr. Long Island flock to the trattoria as part of their annual Bill-gramage to see where the Piano Man once gyrated on the hood of cars and flung filthy rags. They always order the Taglietelle and you should too. It's totally delicious.
Love this little side bar spot. Super great staff and a regular following. Their specials are always worth exploring.

This place  was fabulous.  Perfect dinner outside on a beautiful evening.  Service was spot on. Everyone practiced Covid protocol.  Felt safe. These people know what they are doing with quality and food too. Giving these guys a 5 star makes me want to change all of my other 5 star reviews to a 4. It doesn't get much better than this.
Food was nice. They have a limited lunch menu, but are doing best to serve. Pasta was very good. Frittata dry.
New to the spot but part of what makes a place great is the company you're with.

In a city of countless Italian restaurants, this is a true local gem. Oxtail, carpaccio, and black kale salad for apps, ragu and seasonal pasta/risotto for main, fritters for dessert.

My friend and I shared the rabbit entree with the polenta ..... ughhhh wish I could eat that every day  & we also shared the black spaghetti with the squid it was yummmyyyy. Ended the night with the special dessert (banana bread with ice cream). Will definitely be coming back it was worth every penny we left full and content.  Also side note before we ordered we had trouble picking what we wanted to eat because everything looked amazing and our server was so helpful and patient with us. Service was fast and efficient.

We had a bolognese-ish pasta, some beet and cheese ravioli, and liver. The bolognese was was completely unremarkable, the ravioli was good and probably the best dish of the meal but also not unique, the liver was probably our fault for ordering but also wasn’t interesting. It was exactly as described. Despite higher ceilings and no music, the restaurant was extremely noisy, making it not the ideal location for a romantic evening.

The place itself it’s rather nice and according to many reviews it serves quite good food. Unfortunately we made a bad experience with the pasta today. We had the carbonara as well as the tagliatelle ragu and both dishes were unbalanced and served not as hot as I might have expected. Especially the carbonara had a very strong butter taste where it should be more of a lovely cream taste and the pecorino had a slightly bitter taste in the end which gave a strange combination together with the butter flavor. The tagliatelle ragu was pretty heavy and reminded me of some value ravioli I always avoided to buy in Germany. Overall I presume they serve delicious food but I would recommend not to go for the pasta.

Me and my new wife visited this restaurant on a recommendation, we made the journey across from manhattan especially so as to enjoy a nice meal on our honeymoon during our brief stay in New York.  I can see why this place was recommended as the food was fabulous, however after a long day in the rain we were told by the, as someone else describes her in another review, 'arrogant woman on the door' that we could 'sit there'!  Fair enough as it was busy, but we were wet and pretty cold after being out most of the day and were sat right by the door.  Breeze from the door kept making us more uncomfortable every time it was opened, so we asked to be moved, the staff did not help move us,  despite free seats elsewhere but let us continue to be cold, not very impressed .   We began to feel ever more unwelcome by the staff as the night went on, feeling rushed out the place as the bill was slammed down without us requesting it and also being taken away faster than I could place my card down.  Nice food and a couple of nice staff, however the whole experience is not welcoming or special which I would expect for the price!! Work on your people skills, very disappointing honeymoon meal out!

This corner restaurant in Brooklyn is a gem of fresh and creative Italian cuisine. Lunch specialities include delicious mushroom dishes and fresh homemade pastas. I highly recommend the ragu. The former wine bar which is entered on Carroll Street around the corner from the Fifth Avenue entrance is now a coffee shop. We had excellent teas. I had a chai that was savory - not sweet like many chai teas. Excellent. My companion had chamomile, which she loved. We had two to three cups from the tea pot. The cups themselves are thick, so they hold the heat well. We shared a scone, which was good. Relaxed atmosphere, helpful but not intrusive barista. Good setting. Sunday Times for perusing. What stands out is the attention to quality.

Perfect meal. The beet ravioli were beautiful, and the braised rabbit with polenta was sheer excellence. The staff were also very kind. Highly recommend.

One of my go to Italian restaurants in Brooklyn. Their gnocchi and braised fish dishes are really good.
When we moved to Park Slope, everyone said we had to try al di la! We finally did, and it didn't disappoint. The service was particularly excellent. I had the saltimbocca and it was delicious.

I have been eating here for 13 years...  tonight I decided to take my wife for dinner ,we always sit in the little side street "wine bar" area ...   the waiter was some Italian guy (I only say this so the manager reading this knows of whom I speak about )  the place was completely empty .  I asked him to put my wife's order in first , literally 1 minute later , I put my pasta order in' I ordered  the ragu ... literally 1 minute later .  We waited , 2 people arrived and sat at the bar ....  the server was immediately friendly with them ...  my wife ordered a Whole fish ...  her food arrived , we thought it was normal as she put it in 1 minute prior to me...  she started eating I asked her not to wait ....  the people at the bar received their pasta , ate , finished .   At not one point did the waiter come back to my table to ask if I needed anything or to tell me the status of my order or to offer me a glass of wine ....    My wife finished her food , she wanted to walk out and so did I....   I was so angry I was ready to punch the waiter .   He also creeped my wife out .   Fix this .  Your food is on par with what I cook at home , the house Barbera was a black cherry fruit bomb ....     I would normally not complain because it's just house wine but in this case scenario you start to realize all of these little things,   my wife even told me my fish is better ...  We don't come to this place because the food is outstanding we come just because we like the vibe of the little wine bar....   there is normally a girl there at the wine bar who is the server ,  maybe she's a manager ?  she has curly red Brown hair and she is a sweetheart ....    I spent a $113 I was even kind enough to leave a $15 tip I wanted to leave him $0 I wanted to punch him .  My family owns a number of restaurants in the the west village and in Brooklyn,  this is not the way business should be done.

This Brooklyn landmark has a strong reputation - and it is very well deserved. Solid little cafe run by the folks at...well you guessed it, Al Di La.  If you haven't been to the main restaurant on the corner (this little cafe sits on Carrol, not on fifth), you're missing out. The dinner there is amazing, and the brunch is solid as well (you could argue the service is quite slow, but the quality of the food more than makes up for it). Anywho, the cafe shares the same kitchen as the restaurant and the same quality. It has been a WHILE since I was "wowed' by an egg sandwich, but the one here was friggin' amazing (and not terrible at 6$). The Americano I had was also very very good, as was the drip coffee my fiancee had (so I'm told). Bonus, drip coffee refills are only a buck each, so there is that.  This is a super laid back spot where you could easily get some work done and be well fed in the process; stop by on a lazy Sunday morning to see the Park Slope locals lounging about (I'll be in the last booth on the left)

A gem of not just Park Slope but I think truly the quintessential NYC neighborhood restaurant.  Chef Klinger’s impeccable and unfussy cooking has kept us coming back over and over for 20 years and the welcoming room and friendly service play their part as well.  It’s equally great for a romantic dinner for two (I proposed to my wife here, after all!) as it is for a large gathering of friends and/or family with the cozy shared large tables. Highlights include the rabbit, the risotto, any soup, the tagliatelle al ragu, the malfatti, the casunziei, the whole fish, the seppia and oxtails, and the ribs (some of which are occasional specials), finishing off with the torta di pere or the affogato.  Prices for food and wine are outstanding as well.

Al Di La Trattoria is a classic date night place in Park Slope. They serve up delicious Italian food in a really intimate environment. Seating is at long tables, so sometimes you have to deal with annoying people next to you, but it really does contribute to the intimate environment. The reason you go there is the food though. They make amazing homemade pasta, including things that I've loved including squid ink pasta and rigatoni. Both tasted like they were just rolled out and cooked. The mussel appetizer is to die for. The garlic bread and muscles go perfectly with the sauce. This place gets busy though, so prepared to wait a bit, or make sure to get there at a good time. It's worth the wait though!
